<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09059d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09059d">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09059d"> 59(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> clock stopped at wake / (Kerry)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Kerry Murder / Brothers-in-Law Freed on Slaying Charge / Night at Wake / Failure to Stop Clock Offends Custom</b> The trial was resumed, at the Commission in Green street Courthouse yesterday, before Mr. Justice Pim, of John O&apos;Neill and James O&apos;Sullivan, who are charged with the murder of Michael O&apos;Neill on the morning of June 19, 1922, near Killorglin, Co. Kerry.&hellip; Changing Chairs &hellip; William Joy, farmer, examined by Mr. Cullinane, gave evidence about attending the wake. He noticed a clock going. <mark>It was customary at wakes in Kerry to stop the clock</mark>. He was surprised.&hellip; James Macgillicuddy, a farmer of 20 acres &hellip; saw the clock on the table. It was turned up-side down on the window, going. He never saw a clock going at a wake in Kerry before (laughter). Kerry Customs Mr McElligott&mdash;People might laugh, but people had their customs in Kerry. It was the custom in Kerry to stop the clock at a wake. It could have been turned down to stop it. <small> <a name="FJ27feb24" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FJ27feb24"><cite title="source">Freeman's Journal</cite></a> (27 February 1924) 7/3</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
